-- 
Fairchild, First Solar, Washington Federal: U.S. Equity Movers

-- B y   L u   W a n g
-- 
2011-04-14T15:38:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-13/buckeye-compuware-universal-forest-u-s-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
are having unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of 11:20 a.m. in New York.  Fairchild Semiconductor International Inc. (FCS)   fell
the most in the Russell 1000 Index, sliding 6.2 percent to $18.
The  San Jose , California-based chipmaker said its cash priority
is to support company operations, and it may consider share
buybacks and dividends after it reaches $250 million in cash.  First Solar Inc. (FSLR)   slipped 4 percent to $138.93 for
the biggest retreat in the Standard and Poor’s 500 Index. Bruce
Sohn will step down as president of operations of the world’s
largest maker of thin-film photovoltaic panels at the end of
this month. He may be leaving to become chief executive of
another solar company, an analyst at Auriga USA LLC said. Sohn
won’t be replaced, First Solar said.  Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (GS)   fell 2.6 percent to
$155.94 and dropped as much as 2.9 percent, the most intraday
since Feb. 22. The bank misled clients and Congress about
investments in securities tied to mortgages, the chairman of the
Senate panel that investigated the financial crisis said.
Senator  Carl Levin  said he wants the  Justice Department  and the
Securities and Exchange Commission to examine whether Goldman
Sachs violated the law by misleading clients who bought the
collateralized debt obligations without knowing the firm was
betting they would fall in value.  Iron Mountain Inc. (IRM)   had the third-biggest gain in
the  S&P 500 , adding 3.7 percent to $34.18. The document-storage
company under pressure from investors to make strategic changes
said Chief Executive Officer and President Bob Brennan is
stepping down effective immediately.  Jammin Java Corp. (JAMN)   rallied 37 percent to $1.67
after surging as much as 38 percent, the most intraday since
Dec. 23. The producer of organic coffee from the Blue Mountain
region of Jamaica said it will introduce new coffee and tea
products, including single-serve coffee pods.  J.B. Hunt Transport Services Inc. (JBHT US) increased 6.4
percent to $47.45 and climbed to $48.15 earlier, the highest
intraday price since at least July 1984. The trucking company
reported first-quarter earnings of 40 cents a share, beating the
average analyst estimate of 38 cents a share, according to
Bloomberg data.  Reckitt Benckiser Group Plc (RBGPY)   fell 8.2 percent to
$10.14 for the biggest intraday decline since May 7. The world’s
biggest maker of household cleaners said Chief Executive Officer
Bart Becht, who has led the company since its creation more than
a decade ago, will step down.  Rue21 Inc. (RUE)   rose 4.3 percent to $29.84 and advanced
to $29.94 earlier, the highest intraday price since March 30.
The teen specialty retailer will replace RC2 Corp. (RCRC US) in
the Standard & Poor’s SmallCap 600 Index after the close of
trading on April 20, S&P said in a statement. RC2 is being
acquired by the Tomy Company Ltd. (7867 JP).  Shamaran Petroleum Corp. (SHASF)   rallied 13 percent to
$1.03 and surged 24 percent earlier, the most intraday since
April 2009. The oil explorer with operations in  Iraqi Kurdistan 
reported what it called “a major oil discovery.”  State Bancorp Inc. (STBC US) advanced 3.2 percent to $10.35
and gained 5.1 percent earlier, the most intraday since March
17. The holding company for  State Bank  of  Long Island  reported
first-quarter earnings of 15 cents a share, above the 13-cent a
share average of estimates among analysts surveyed by Bloomberg.  Supervalu Inc. (SVU)   gained 14 percent to $10.34 for the
biggest increase in the S&P 500. The owner of Save-A-Lot and Cub
Foods grocery stores reported fourth-quarter earnings of 44
cents a share, excluding certain items, beating the 34-cent
average analyst estimate.  Universal Forest Products Inc. (UFPI)   slid 8.9 percent
to $30.63 and slumped 11 percent earlier, the most intraday
since Oct. 14. The maker of do-it-yourself lumber products
reported a first-quarter loss of 19 cents a share, missing the
average analyst estimate for a profit 1 cent a share, Bloomberg
data show.  Washington Federal Inc. (WFSL)   fell 5.2 percent to
$15.72 after erasing 5.3 percent earlier, the most intraday
since Aug. 6. JPMorgan Chase & Co. said the Seattle-based  bank
holding company  reduced posted second-quarter profit excluding
some items of 18 cents a share, missing the estimate of 24 cents
by analyst Steven Alexopoulos.  Zipcar Inc. (ZIP US) surged 59 percent to $28.62 on its
first day of trading. The car-sharing company that rents
vehicles by the hour raised $174.3 million in an initial public
offering, 31 percent more than it sought, after it increased the
shares and priced them above the range.  To contact the reporter on this story:
